Write a program for the following:  an inner class named Inner is defined within the scope of class Outer.Therefore, any code in class Inner can directly access the variable 
outer_x. An instance method named display( ) is defined inside Inner. This method displays outer_x on the standard output stream.The main( ) method of InnerClassDemo creates
an instance of class Outer and invokes its test( ) method. That method creates an instance of class Inner and the display( ) method is called.

import java.util.Scanner;
class Outer //outer class
{
Scanner readme=new Scanner(System.in);
int outer_x=readme.nextInt();
public void test()  //test method of outer class
{
Inner i=new Inner();
i.display();
}
class Inner  //inner class
{
public void display()  //display method of inner class
{
System.out.println("the value is: "+outer_x);
}
}
}
class InnerClassDemo  //InnerClassDemo calling the test method of outer class
{
public static void main(String[] args)
{
Outer o=new Outer();
o.test();
}
}

